    <TD>Chair</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR><STRONG>Group Summary:</STRONG><BR>
<DIV 
style="PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; PADDING-TOP: 0px">The 
Particle and Nuclear Physics Applications Research Group provides a forum for 
discussion of issues related to particle and nuclear physics applications and 
production grids.<BR><BR></DIV><STRONG>Charter Focus/Purpose and 
Scope:</STRONG><BR>
<DIV 
style="PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; PADDING-TOP: 0px">The 
Particle and Nuclear Physics Applications Research Group provides a forum for 
discussion of issues related to particle and nuclear physics applications as 
well as production grids. <BR><BR>There are five specific goals, all with the 
overarching aim of ensuring that HENP actively participates in setting 
requirements and defining standards to ensure that its needs are met and to 
bring its experiences in deploying and using large scale grids to the grid 
community as a whole. <BR>• To bring the requirements of the HENP community to 
the GGF in order to explain and inform the wider grid community of the specific 
needs and issues of HENP, e.g. in the form of documented key points. <BR>• To 
ensure participation of the HENP community in grid standardization efforts, 
particularly in those areas and services essential to the successful use of 
grids in HENP. <BR>• To provide early feedback to GGF technical working groups 
on the success or failure of various grid software components as used in high 
performance production activities by HENP experiments. <BR>• To provide early 
feedback to HENP about ongoing activites in the GGF, relevant to the HENP 
community, as well as to ease knowledge transfer. This could be done in the form 
of presentations at relevant HENP meetings. <BR>• To ensure that relevant HENP 
applications such as PROOF or simulation frameworks (Geant3/4) run on todays 
Grid environments. <BR>The particle and nuclear physics community has over the 
past few years provided the driving applications and made significant 
contributions to several projects. <BR>These projects have been actively 
involved in deploying production grid applications. Many members of the HENP 
community are instrumental in existing or new GGF working or research groups. 
Current areas of interest include security, high throughput data transport, data 
intensive management and access services, as well as information schema 
definition. As the community continues to develop and adopt higher level and 
more comprehensive services it is anticipated that we will further contribute to 
other areas of work. These include production and operations services, 
scheduling and job description, databases, frameworks and applications, and also 
network and resource management.<BR><BR>The PNPA Research Group will provide a 
venue to bring together HENP application developers with the information 
scientists and researchers in grid technologies at the OGF. HENP experiments are 
deploying petascale production grids now. We aim to identify the requirements 
of, and communicate experiences from, these deployments as they relate to the 
OGF. We believe there are important commonalities in requirements across the 
experiments in the field which can be collected and documented as a common set. 
<BR>Members of this Research Group will include representatives of the grid 
projects (EGEE, WLCG, OSG, …) in the field. These projects must deliver and 
deploy production grid middleware and services to enable scientific analysis on 
a global scale. The research group will also ensure that grid developments 
driven by the larger HENP projects will also be compatible and useable by other 
experiments within HENP. <BR><BR><BR></DIV><STRONG>Exit Strategy</STRONG>:<BR>
<DIV 
style="PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; PADDING-TOP: 0px">Particle 
Physics Initiatives, with the Large Hadron Collider at CERN being the primary 
example, have average life times in the range of 20 years. Grid and application 
development thus has to be an ongoing process and standards being developed as 
part of this group have to be continuously revised and updated. It is expected 
that the amount of time needed for standardisation discussions decreases after 
LHC has reached its design luminosity. However, as Particle Physics experiments 
with even higher data rates such as the FAIR project at GSI Darmstadt become 
operational, further significant work will be needed. No fixed life time for 
this research group is therefore envisaged. 
